+**Chosen order: [write commit object, create ref, store.integrate_trial]**
+with compensating ref-delete on store failure.
 
+Rationale for each step:
+
+1. **Write commit object** (step 8 of the algorithm). Content-addressed;
+   the object exists but nothing points at it. Unreachable git objects
+   are invisible to every reader who traverses refs — the normal reader
+   path. `git gc` prunes them on its own schedule. Writing the object
+   first has no observable effect.
+2. **Create ref** (step 9). `create_ref` with zero-oid is a CAS: if the
+   ref already exists, `GitError` propagates. This gives the sole-writer
+   discipline (§1.2) a mechanical guard on top of the protocol rule.
+3. **`store.integrate_trial`** (step 10). The store commits
+   `trial_commit_sha` and the `trial.integrated` event atomically. On
+   success, all three artifacts are observable. On failure, the ref
+   exists but the other two do not — the compensating delete restores
+   the pre-integration state.
+
+**On compensating-delete failure** — if step 10 raises and
+`repo.delete_ref(...)` also raises, neither rollback path succeeded.
+The integrator raises `AtomicityViolation` wrapping both causes. This
+is the one state §3.4 explicitly acknowledges as requiring
+implementation-defined mitigation; the wrapped exception documents
+exactly which ref is dangling so an operator can delete it manually.
+
+**Transient-window note.** Between steps 9 and 10 the ref exists but
+the trial field/event do not. The §1.2 sole-integrator rule means no
+*protocol-conforming* concurrent reader of `trial/*` within the in-
+process reference implementation observes this window under the
+dispatch loop's sequential driver (`_promote_successful_trials`).
+External readers (e.g. `git log trial/*` from a shell) MAY transiently
+observe the ref before the field/event land; per §3.4's permission for
+compensating deletes, such a reader would see the ref disappear on
+rollback. The post-stabilization invariant (§3.4 closing sentence) is
+what every subsequent reader observes. The reference implementation
+does not attempt stronger instantaneous consistency, because no
+mechanism permitted by §3.4 (outbox, compensating delete, store-level
+transaction against a separate git process) can give a zero-width
+window against external filesystem readers without coordination that
+the spec does not require.
